You don't see things in absolutes? Hmm.<br>
Am I trying to fix certain things in my life? Of course I am...but I happen to enjoy my one smoke.<br>
<br>
&quot;Obviously your views are totally biased. There are people who have quit, if you don't realize that, well....back to the cave, I guess.&quot;<br>
<br>
 Read it all together, not dissected. Your bias is seeing people die...and not seeing people quit. You see smoking = not able to quit = death. That simply isn't the case. It's not an absolute truth. Don't get all sensitive. Obviously you do know people can quit. Therfore your not a caveman....are you?<br>
But....<br>
Sure, I have a smoke once a week...for the same reason you prolly have that occassional donut or hamburger.<br>
<br>
Yes yes yes, I am drawing conclusions...conclusions set up by your posts. And I sure do wish I had a killer Irish accent. Guess I should have spent more time with Grammy... <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
And yes, the tattoo thing is really that simple. Don't assume I just woke up one morning and said I think I'll get a random tattoo on a random part of my body from some random person. What I'm saying is that that one particular design doesn't mean anything. It's just a nice design, a design I was proud of. I'm proud of my body, proud of my art. There's no secret to my feelings on my body, no hidden mystery of the universe in it, or why I get tats. The others, yes they have meaning. <br>
<br>
You said people are not blank slates. Not blank slates = having a preconcieved notion, an achetype of an individuals personality. If you go into something with a preconcieved notion of what that person must be like...ok. I.E. You meet me. You say wow, why did you get your tat. I say, because I liked the design. You obviously don't beleive me...there must be some hidden agenda to WHY I got this particular tat. That's what I meant.<br>
<br>
&quot;Everything about a person makes them who they are. To ignore any part of it is to ignore some part of that person. Would you want someone to ignore you? Even the smallest part of you? &quot;<br>
<br>
Yes, actually. If I was ugly. If I was fat. The fact that I'm white. I really don't care too much about a person exterior. I concern myself more with the interior. What's on the outside can be icing on the cake, or I ignore it in favor of their other more endearing qualities. Like my friend who thinks she's fat when she's not. Or my other friend who has an annoying laugh. I'll ignore the bad...the annoying laugh...and say cool...she's laughing. Or my dog barking at strangers. <br>
<br>
So that's that. Maybe I did read into your statements...maybe not. Whatever, I didn't think we were fighting. Your opinion on smokers is just fine with me. I happen to have similar views....although I tend to have more compassion for people with substance abuse problems.<br>
<br>
I guess we'll just have to agree to disagree. <p><Font color="#FF0033" link="#FF0033" vlink="#FF0033" alink="#000066"> 


